{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512820","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512820"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:01:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:01:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11963"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11963","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11963"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.22,0.09,0.49,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4555"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109050"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4555","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4555"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11963"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91416"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"449"},{"type":"tags","id":"1004"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"2194"},{"type":"tags","id":"3709"},{"type":"tags","id":"12909"},{"type":"tags","id":"12917"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6818"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6893"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109050","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109050"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman is electively admitted to start a course of chemotherapy for her acute myeloid leukaemia. She is on no medications at home and is started on enoxaparin at admission. Her full blood count (FBC) at admission shows mild anaemia and normal platelets, with a slightly elevated white cell count.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn day 10 of her chemotherapy cycle, her FBC shows Haemoglobin 69 g/L (125 - 160), platelets 27x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (150 - 450) and neutrophils 0.3x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (1.8 \u2013 7.5). She is haemodynamically stable and has had a Group and Hold in the last 72 hours.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"After reviewing these blood results, which one of the following is the next most appropriate step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Examine the patient and if they are fine, do nothing","Request urgent blood products to be sent to the ward","Transfuse one bag platelets","Transfuse one unit RBCs and cease enoxaparin","Infuse 2 L of normal saline"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAction and intervention need to be taken with this patient. As a result of the myelosuppression caused by her chemotherapy, she is both anaemic and thrombocytopenic, however, this does not necessarily mean her counts fall within transfusion guidelines. There is no strict rule for transfusion of RBC, but a haemoglobin of \u0026lt;70 g/L is commonly used. In this case, as she has active leukaemia and has received chemotherapy, it would be reasonable to aim for a Hb even higher and some haematology/oncology units will set their transfusion target at 80 g/L. Regardless, this woman \u003Cstrong\u003Eneeds at least one unit of RBCs\u003C/strong\u003E. In terms of the thrombocytopenia, while this is very low, low platelets are tolerated until they are \u0026lt;10x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L when spontaneous bleeding is more likely to occur. So in this case, she \u003Cstrong\u003Edoes not require a platelet transfusion\u003C/strong\u003E. The platelet count is relevant though for the use of prophylactic enoxaparin. For platelet counts below 30 - 50x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L, venous thromboembolism (VTE) chemoprophylaxis is not indicated. So her \u003Cstrong\u003Eenoxaparin needs to be ceased\u003C/strong\u003E since her platelets have dropped. It can be restarted if her platelets increase to above 50x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent blood products,\u003C/strong\u003E in this case, are not necessary as this is not an emergency. The patient does require blood products, but she is not acutely bleeding and is haemodynamically stable. A Group and Hold has been done, so once the blood products have been ordered there is no rush to get them to the ward and patient. Giving \u003Cstrong\u003Enormal saline\u003C/strong\u003E may be appropriate if the patient was hypotensive, but she would still require correction of her anaemia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["VTE chemoprophylaxis is not indicated in patients with platelets below 30-50x10^9 /L"],"references":["Gehrie EA. Transfusion support in acute leukemia: what is the evidence to support routine practices? Transfusion. 2017;57(2):229-233. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28194854/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91416"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11963"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91416","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91416"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-16T15:53:12+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-16T15:53:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4555"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109050"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"head